Foodborne Chicago Survey Analysis

Cory Nissen

12/31/2014

Introduction

Within 7 months of launching Foodborne Chicago with the help of the Smart Chicago Collaborative and the Chicago Health Department back in April of 2013, we noticed that many of the complaints generated through the system were on the north side of the city, with very few coming from the south side. In November 2013, we created several maps of the submissions to visualize this phenomenon. The Knight foundation helped us with funding via their prototype fund to investigate reasons why this might be. We used some of those funds to run a survey of Chicago residents.

Survey Set Up

The survey was run on Chicago residents that have used Twitter recently. It was administered online by SSI from December 11, 2014 to December 19, 2014. There were 6 screener questions and 16 regular questions on the survey. We were aiming for a good mix of north side and south side residents. We had 91 completed surveys, with 56 on the north side and 35 on the south side. For the purposes of our analysis, north side is defined as north of the line that the northern edge of zip codes 60623, 60608, 60616 create across the city. Zip codes 60623, 60608, 60616 and those to the south are considered south side. Much of the analysis to follow will focus on this somewhat arbitrary line.
